                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <locus from="3r" to="133v"/>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (different kinds of red)</seg>
                        <date notBefore="1882" notAfter="1889">late 19th century</date>
                        <desc>The hand is sometimes fine (e.g. on <locus target="#59r #87r"/>), more often mediocre and right-slanted (e.g. on <locus target="#4r #57r #119r"/>). 
                           Most probably several hands were involved in the writing.
                           Among the scribal practices, the letters <foreign xml:lang="gez">ግዚ</foreign> are often written with a ligature; 
                           <foreign xml:lang="gez">tamallas</foreign>-signs in the shape of two perpendicular lines are used on <locus target="#57r #65r"/> to indicate the omission of 
                           one or more words (the omitted words are written in the upper margin).
                        </desc>
                        <seg type="rubrication">
                           Several groups of lines on the incipit pages, alternating with black lines (e.g. <locus target="#5r #58r"/>); refrains and other words in abbreviated form (e.g. 
                           <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስብ</foreign> for <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስብሐት፡</foreign> (<locus target="#78r"/>); holy names; elements of the punctuation 
                           signs and of the Ethiopic numerals. Texts <ref target="#ms_i11"/> and <ref target="#ms_i12"/> have not been rubricated.
                        </seg>
